06050nam a22007935i 9781501728365DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20182008nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017283657 a10.7591/97815017283652doi  a(DE-B1597)515200  a(OCoLC)1100441717  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0460002bisacsh04a171/.2/09222300aAquinas's Moral Theory :bEssays in Honor of Norman Kretzmann /ced. by Scott MacDonald, Eleonore Stump. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tModern Editions of Aquinas's Works -- tIntroduction -- tI. Moral Theory And Moral Theology -- tAquinas on Aristotelian Happiness -- tWisdom: Will, Belief, and Moral Goodness -- tSaint Thomas and the Principle of Double Effect -- tIdeals of Scientia moralis and the Invention of the Summa theologiae -- tII. Moral Psychology And Practical Reason -- tAquinas on the Passions -- tPractical Reasoning and Reasons-Explanations: Aquinas's Account of Reason's Role in Action -- tAquinas on Exceptions in Natural Law -- tIII. Moral Theory In Philosophy Of Language And Metaphysics -- tAquinas on Significant Utterance: Interjection, Blasphemy, Prayer -- tThomas Aquinas on the Good: The Relation between Metaphysics and Ethics -- tDegrees of Being, Degrees of Goodness: Aquinas on Levels of Reality -- tNorman Kretzmann's Publications on Aquinas -- tContributors -- tReferences to Aquinass Works -- tIndex of Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAquinas's discussions of moral issues are extensive, and range well beyond the narrowly defined set of issues in the modern tradition of moral philosophy. This volume explores the ethical dimensions of a wide selection of philosophical and theological topics in Aquinas's texts. It covers topics central to ethics, such as happiness, moral virtue, and natural law, as well as related topics pertaining to the metaphysical basis of Aquinas's account of goodness, the ramifications of his ethical concerns for his philosophy of language, and the significance of his philosophical psychology for his ethics.The volume is divided into three sections focusing, respectively, on issues concerning moral theory and moral theology, moral psychology and practical reason, and moral theory in philosophy of language and metaphysics. The authors—distinguished scholars of medieval philosophy—bring to these issues a variety of approaches and viewpoints. By creatively sampling the breadth of Aquinas's reflections on ethical issues and exploring some of the significant connections that tie his moral thought to other parts of his philosophical and theological system, they display the richness and depth of Aquinas's moral thinking.Contributors: Jan A. Aertsen, Thomas-Institut, Cologne; E. Jennifer Ashworth, University of Waterloo; John Boler, University of Washington; Mark D. Jordan, Emory University; Anthony Kenny, Oxford University; Peter King, University of Toronto; Scott MacDonald, Cornell University; Gareth B. Matthews, University of Massachusetts, Amherst; Paul Vincent Spade, Indiana University; Eleonore Stump, Saint Louis University  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEthics, Medieval. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Individual Philosophers.2bisacsh1 aAertsen, Jan A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAshworth, E. Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoler, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJordan, Mark D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r